  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Identifying potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Evaluating potential money laundering risks\n- Developing risk-based compliance strategies\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n\n5. Training\n- Educating employees about money laundering indicators\n- Providing ongoing compliance training\n- Understanding regulatory updates\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potential illegal activities.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific areas?",
